canonical:
  title: 賜金富軾加授同德贊化功臣守太保餘並如故
  author: 崔諴
  language: lzh
  text: 敎富軾卿以先覺之才居具瞻之地雲從龍風從虎道與時行爵有德官有功事稽古制加之名位之峻示以禮貌之尊尙體眷懷往膺休渥今賜卿同德贊化功臣守大保餘如故告身一通至可領也
  rtl: true
  vertical: true
lzh_formatted:
  title: 賜金富軾加授同德贊化功臣守太保餘並如故
  author: 崔諴
  language: lzh
  text: 敎富軾。卿以先覺之才。居具瞻之地。雲從龍風從虎。道與時行。爵有德官有功。事稽古制。加之名位之峻。示以禮貌之尊。尙體眷懷。往膺休渥。今賜卿同德贊化功臣守大保。餘如故。告身一通。至可領也。
korean:
  title: 찬화공신 수태보를 제수하고 나머지는 모두 전과 같이 한다
  author: 최함
  language: kor
  text: 김부식(金富軾)에게 교하노라. 경은 선각(先覺)의 재주로써 정승의 지위에 처하였다. 구름은 용을 따르고 바람은 범을 따르는지라, 도(道)는 때와 함께 시행되고, 덕이 있는 자에게 작위를 주고 공이 있는 자에게 관직을 주는 것이니, 일은 옛 제도에 의거한다. 명위(名位)를 더하여 존숭하는 예모를 보인다. 바라건대, 권념하는 마음을 체득하여 아름다운 은혜를 받으라. 이제 경에게 동덕 찬화공신 수태보(同德贊化功臣守太保)를 주고 나머지는 전과 같이 한다. 직첩 한 통이 이르거든 잘 받으라.
  url: https://db.itkc.or.kr/dir/item?itemId=BT#dir/node?dataId=ITKC_BT_1365A_0280_010_0030&viewSync=OT
  footnotes: []
english:
  title: Conferring the Title of Tongdeok Changhwa Meritorious Subject and Grand Protector upon Kim Bu-sik, with All Other Matters Remaining as Before
  author: Choe Ham
  language: eng
  text: |-
    An edict to Kim Bu-sik:

    You, with the wisdom of one who perceives before others, have taken your place in a position of highest regard. As clouds follow the dragon and wind follows the tiger, so the Way proceeds with the times. Rank rewards virtue, office rewards merit—such is the ancient precedent we honor. We elevate your name and station to demonstrate the respect owed to you. Cherish this mark of Our favor and receive the gracious bestowment We grant.

    We hereby confer upon you the title of Meritorious Subject of Tongdeok and Changhwa, and appoint you Grand Protector. All other matters remain as they were. Your certificate of appointment shall be delivered—receive it well.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: Tongdeok Changhwa Meritorious Subject (同德贊化功臣) was a high official title in Goryeo, bestowed upon those who contributed to the state's governance and virtue.
  - key: ''
    value: Grand Protector (太保) was one of the three highest ranks in the Goryeo bureaucratic system, typically held by senior statesmen.
  - key: ''
    value: The imagery of clouds following dragons and wind following tigers is a classical metaphor for natural harmony between ruler and virtuous officials.
